ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, we present an innovative sensor specifically designed for the parallel and precise detection of Cr6+ and Fe3+ in various environments based on CDs derived from extracts of Poria cocos. Specifically, the assay was extremely sensitive towards both Cr6+ and Fe3+ with limit of detection (LOD) of 1.07 × 10−3 nM and 1.98 × 10−3 nM, respectively; which were remarkably lower than previously reported values (
                        Tables S1 & S2
                     ). Furthermore, the assay was also highly selective for Cr6+ and Fe3+, free from interference in the presence of majority of common ions even in complex environments. Systematic mechanism explorations revealed that the possible fluorescence quenching pathways for Cr6+ and Fe3+ were inner filter effect (IFE) and static quenching, respectively. Encouragingly, the assay demonstrated consistent performances in various real samples including mineral water, tap water, lake water and serum, with recoveries of both Cr6+ and Fe3+ maintained within acceptable error limits in all circumstances, highlighting its high utility in practical applications. It is particularly noteworthy that we employed multiple strategies to differentiate Cr6+ and Fe3+, and a corresponding logic gate was constructed. Overall, this assay could provide a promising approach for the efficient and parallel detection of Cr6+ and Fe3+.

Indeed, it was clearly shown that PL emissions of CDs at 445 nm gradually decreased as the Cr6+ concentrations increased from 0 to 300 μM (Fig. 3
                        b), the same trend could also be visually observed in which the color of the CDs dispersions gradually changed from bright blue to dark (
                           Fig. S3
                        ). In order to quantitatively illustrate the relationship between Cr6+ concentration and the PL intensity of CDs, a plot with the PL intensity denoting the y-axis and Cr6+ concentration denoting the x-axis was plotted (Fig. 3
                        c). Clearly, the plot exhibited good linear relationship between the PL intensity of CDs and the Cr6+ concentration in the range of 0–130 and 130–300 μM. The linear equations of the fitted curves were determined as F = 2323235–9255[Cr6+], R2 = 0.98 (Fig. 3
                        d), and F = 1650035–4096[Cr6+], R2 = 0.98 (
                           Fig. S4
                        ), respectively. This LOD was determined to be 1.07 × 10−3 nM based on Fig. 3d according to the well-accepted 3σ method (LOD = 3σ/k, where σ is the standard deviation of at least 20 blank samples and k is the slope of the linear calibration curve). To our excitement, the LOD of our assay was much lower than not only the maximum allowable value (9.60 μM) for Cr6+ content in industrial effluent in China [39] but also the values previously reported (
                           Table S1
                        ).

Similarly, PL intensities of CDs were also negatively correlated to Fe3+ concentrations (Fig. 3
                        e) within two linear ranges from 0–300 μM and 300–750 μM, respectively (Fig. 3
                        f). The linear equations of the fitting curves were determined to be F = 2415913–4999[Fe3+], R2 = 0.99 (
                           Fig. S5
                        ), and F = 1229427–897[Fe3+], R2 = 0.97 (
                           Fig. S6
                        ). In addition, the color of the CDs dispersions also gradually changed from bright blue to dark with 360 nm excitation as the Fe3+ concentrations were gradually increased from 0 to 750 μM (
                           Fig. S7
                        ). The LOD was determined to be 1.98 × 10−3 nM based on the calibration curve in 
                           Fig. S5, which was much lower than the maximum allowable level of Fe3+ in drinking water set by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (5.4 μM) [40] and the values reported previously (
                           Table S2
                        ).

However, the mimicked environment for the above trials was in DI water. Therefore, we ran additional tests to determine the suitability of the assay for use in real water environments. To begin with, the presence of metal ions in mineral water, tap water and lake water samples was carefully assessed using the assay aforementioned above. As shown (
                           Fig. S8
                        ), the PL intensities of CDs in the three samples were essentially the same as that of CDs in DI water, indicating that the level of metal ions (if any) in these samples was significantly lower than the LOD of the assay. As such, a total of fifteen spike solutions were prepared in mineral water, tap water, lake water and serum. The encouraging results showed that the recoveries were 96.0–100.0 % for mineral water samples (Table 1, entries 5–8), 97.4–104.5 % for tap water samples (entries 9–12), and 92.9–102.6 % for lake water samples (entries 13–16). All exhibited outstanding recoveries, highlighting that the assay was indeed highly practical for the detection of Cr6+ in various real water environments. Based on the foregoing exploration in real water samples, we further extended Cr6+ detection to biological sample (serum). To our delight, the recoveries of the serum samples were 104.8–109.4 % (entries 17–19), which are also within the detection tolerance.

Next, we carefully compared the emission and excitation spectra of CDs with the UV–vis absorption of Cr6+ (Fig. 4
                        c). It was obvious that there was a large overlap between the excitation spectrum of CDs (blue curve) and the absorption of Cr6+ (black curve) in the range from 310 to 425 nm, indicating that the quenching of CDs PL by Cr6+ 
                        via IFE mechanism is possible. To test this hypothesis, Parker’s equation was applied [27,28]. The quenching factor (CF) is an import term in IFE as it reflects the degree of PL intensity reduction due to the IFE quenching effect and could be quantitatively calculated (Eq. 

                           (2)
                        ). As showing, the CF values gradually increased along with the Cr6+ concentrations (
                           Table S5
                        ), indicating that IFE indeed contributed to the quenching of CDs PL by Cr6+. To quantitatively evaluate the contribution of IFE to the quenching of CDs PL, we further calculated the inhibition efficiency (IE) in the presence of Cr6+ of varied concentrations (Eqs. 

                           (3) & (4)
                        ). Based on the data obtained (
                           Table S5
                        ), a plot showing the IE values with (red line) and without (black line) correction was shown (Fig. 4
                        d). To our surprise, IFE took account more than 90 % of the total quenching when Cr6+ concentration was 75 µM (
                           Table S5
                        ) based on a simple calculation (Eq. 

                           (5)
                        ), highlighting that IFE mechanism played a dominant role in the quenching of CDs PL [45]. Collectively consider all the above evidences, we cautiously propose that the quenching of CDs PL by Cr6+ most likely went through the IFE pathway.
